<h1> User Defined Types </h1>

<div class=well><samp>
"Any fool can write code that a computer
can understand. Good programmers write 
code that humans can understand." - Martin Fowler
</samp></div>
	
<h2> Managing the Mess </h2>

<P>
Embedded code has a tendancy to get messy. 
More so, I would argue, then
code written for a high-level application. 
Masks and addresses in hexadecimal, 
strange types defined by obscure libraries, 
and usually no classes to wrap them up in.
</P>

<p>
The landscape of an embedded codebase can be
vast, obscure, and complicated; And usually 
by the time you get used to its quirks and
learn its style, its time to move on to 
a different microcontroller with a different 
library. This makes writing clean and readable
code that much more difficult,
and that much more important.
</p>

<p>
This chapter will cover some tools you can use
to make your C code more readable. The following 
concepts will be covered:
</p>

<ul>
	<li>
		Type Definitions (typedef)
	</li>

	<li>
		Fixed Width Integers (uint32_t)
	</li>

	<li>
		Enumerated Types (enums)
	</li>

	<li>
		Structs
	</li>

	<li>
		Unions
	</li>

	<li>
		Bitfeilds
	</li>

	<li>
		Using Unions and Bitfeilds Together
	</li>
	
	<li>
		Preprocessor Directives
	</li>

	<li>
		Volatile Variables
	</li>
		
	<li>
		Static Variables
	</li>
</ul>


